              h: "Document Carousels: The Slow-Scroll Machine",
              body: "LinkedIn document posts (PDF carousels) are dwell-time weapons: every swipe is a measurable engagement event, and a good carousel earns eight to twelve of them per reader.\n\nDesign rules from the agency world:\n\n- **The cover slide is a thumbnail.** Big promise in large type, high contrast, visual hierarchy — it competes in the feed exactly like a YouTube thumbnail competes on the homepage. Weak cover, dead carousel, regardless of interior quality.\n- **One idea per slide.** A slide is a rung, not a page. Around 25-40 words maximum; if a slide needs two ideas, it's two slides.\n- **Design for thumb-speed reading:** minimum ~28pt body type, consistent template, generous margins, progress cues ('3/9') that promise a finish line.\n- **Slide two is the re-hook** — stakes or a roadmap, mirroring the text post's second line.\n- **The final slide carries the CTA** plus a one-slide recap; it's also what shows when people share.\n\nMeasure swipe-through the honest way: does the comment section reference late-slide content? If comments only echo the cover, your interior is losing readers."
