              body: "Experts explain ideas; authorities **name** them. When you coin a framework — 'the Content Waterfall,' 'the 10-before-1 rule,' 'anchor-amplifier-archive' — three things happen that explanation alone never achieves:\n\n1. The idea becomes **citable**. People can now reference it in their own posts and meetings, and every citation carries your name as the source.\n2. The idea becomes **memorable**. A named thing occupies a mental slot; an unnamed insight evaporates by the next scroll.\n3. The idea becomes **defensible territory**. Competitors can teach the same concept, but the name is yours.\n\nThe craft of naming: two to four words, concrete imagery over abstraction ('waterfall' beats 'multi-stage repurposing methodology'), and a slight tension or surprise that makes it sticky.\n\nThen — and this is where most experts fail — **repeat the name relentlessly**. Use it in every relevant post for six months. You will be sick of it long before the market has even registered it. Naming without repetition is just private vocabulary."
